salms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"'The","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Dorothea  , also used independently."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Devil'","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the Irish surname, Gaelic <i>Ó Damháin</i> ‘descendant of <i>Damhán</i>’. The latter is a byname meaning ‘fawn’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"David 'The Devil' Arnot was born in 1306, in Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland as the son of Sir Michael Arnot - Laird of Arnot, Knight and Margery De Fife. He had at least 2 sons with Margery De Fife. He died in 1395, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1306–1395":"1306–1395","–Female":"Surnud","1330–1404":"1330–1404","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1280–1342":"1280–1342","1404":"1404","1342":"1342","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","about 1350":"umbes 1350","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland","Portmoak, Kinross, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1306–1395":"1306–1395","–Female":"Kuollut","1330–1404":"1330–1404","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1280–1342":"1280–1342","1404":"1404","1342":"1342","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","about 1350":"noin 1350","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, 